description.text:
This is a torture test for DualStrusion accuracy - drawing lines of alternating colours from 0.5mm to 4mm in 0.5mm increments.
There seems to be a slight overlap of lines at 0.5mm, but just barely.

1) Open AccuracyTest.gcode in ReplicatorG and print.

comments.text: The resolution looks great, but it also looks like the dual extruders left little bits of colors on the other areas. At least, there look like there are black bits of plastic in the white areas. I guess this would be because extruding can't precisely stop, so there's a little stringing or dripping of the extruder that's not being used, when the other is. Or is something else going on?

comments.text: I have a feeling that the extra bits are getting pushed out due to thermal expansion of the plastic in the unused extruder. At least I think that is the case with my Replicator.

description.text: Coffee Stencil
This part was made with Tinkercad. Edit the part online at: https://tinkercad.com/things/fOIOkAsFVyr

Made with Tinkercad in-browser creator for the #Chess contest. Rules:
  • I thought of these rules but I haven't tried them out. Let me know if they need tweaks.
    • Setup:
    Both players play by setting up their pieces normally. Since there is one side which is a cylinder, the opponent is not really able to see the other pieces, but they can see their own. The trick is to play normally, but once pieces have reached a point where you THINK your opponent forgot what piece is what, you can change your piece's movement into another piece to trick your opponent. Challenges:
    If the opponent feels you are moving a piece falsely, they can issue a challenge. If they catch you in the lie you have to turn the piece halfway permanently to show both players what piece it really is. Challenge of movement can only occur when the player attempts to move the piece. Players are limited in the number of challenges they use - 8 for 'easy', 6 for 'medium', and 4 for 'hard'. Winning conditions:
    If the King moves into check on accident, you may end the game. Otherwise, play until checkmate. When declaring checkmate, attacking player must show all pieces without penalizing the opponent's challenge stock. On rematch (second game and beyond) I suggest switching the pieces around to a different starting point, furthering the confusion. I hope I can try this myself some day with a printed copy. Thank you for looking!

You can find one rim for front tyres (F1Car_MyRimFront.stl) and one for Rear Tyres (F1Car_MyRimRear.stl). They works in the same way of barspin's rim version (just only #2 MR128ZZ bear for the Front Rim).

December 25, 2016
This is a remix of the OpenRC Formula 1 car by Barspin. I had some warping problem with Rear Axle so I splitted it in three pieces (more easy to print).
Just print #2 lateral_RearAxle and #1 Central_Axle. You can assemble it just with #2 m3 screw (12mm lenght).

I also like to use 12hex commercial tyres so I designed new tyre holder for front and rear.
For each front tyres you need #2 MR128ZZ bear (same 8mm inner diameter bear in the barspin's BOM) and #1 F683ZZ (maybe also a normal 683ZZ bear is useful).
No needs for rear tyres. Just fit it in the RearAxle.

I added a servo rod. I use it to assemble servo saver with the servo itself. I doesn't have 1mm steel rod and I printed a simple bar with 2 holes rotated by 90 degree.

Last change is for pignon and spur gear. I listen to someone had problem with pignon (it doesn't work properly after a while because may be it doesn't fit again with motor axle) so I designed a new set of gear 32DP so you can use standard pigno (you can buy it for few euro).

remixed_from.title: DremelFuge - A One-Piece Centrifuge for Rotary Tools

description.text:
PULL-FUGE is a manual rubber band powered Centrifuge, sure it takes more time and effort compared to commercial Hi-tech Centrifuges but much cheaper and can function better in hazard conditions.
It's a cheap solution for medical campaigns held in remote areas in underdeveloped or developing countries where no electricity and low budget field hospitals are expected.

Changes made to the "DremelFuge":
1- Swiveled tube slots same like commercial Centrifuges to ensure that the sediment sample won't mix again after stopping spinning.
2- Enlarged the wheel hub diameter to be tight fitted in the spinner top opening and also to ensure that its centric.
3- Narrowed the tube side access in the swivel carriages as after 1st print the tubes kept flying away at high speeds.
4- Made the tubes hole size less by 0.1mm from original diameter to be snug fit.

Changes made to the "Pull String Helicopter":
It's quite simple to start it from scratch even with more simple design, but why wasting the time while it's already there and functioning?

1- Modified the spinner head to suite the modified "DremelFuge" hub.

Tips:
1- To make the rubber band last longer; Soak it thoroughly in talcum powder.
2- Use a strong long lasting string like a fishing line.
3- To avoid vibrations Swivel carriages should be balanced; all tubes should be placed and filled with approximately same volume.

Instructions:
1.Insert the Spinner in the handle.
2.Tie the string to the spinner upper hole.
String length not to be more than 50cm.
3.Pass the rubber band through the spinner end eye hole.
Rubber band size used is no.64 (3-1.2" x 1/4").
4.Force the 2 band loops down to the end of the handle then hook them with a pen or a stick.
5.Rotate the pen/stick around 15 turns holding the spinner from turning.
6.Release the spinner slowly keeping the string under slight tension winding it back until the band becomes straight.
7.Either print the knob from the original design (Pull String Helicopter) or use any other object as a knob.
8.Pull the string back winding the band 3 turns then tie the knob as close as possible to the handle.
9.Replace the pen/stick with the printed stopper.
10.Finally, insert the wheel with the tube swivel carriages through the spinner slots and you are ready to go!

title: Snap-together Heart Lattice
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Putting up lights is fun, but it's even more fun to put them up in the shape of something. Grab some LED Christmas lights (or whatever your fancy is) and intertwine them in this some-assembly-required heart frame.

The final heart is around a meter wide and has mounting holes for placement on a wall.

You will need all eighteen pieces. Don't be scared - they print in batches of three or four in no time at all.

Printer Brand:

FlashForge

Printer:

FlashForge Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

50

Notes:

The frame consists of eighteen thin parts that can be conveniently printed three or four at a time. All parts can be printed without rafts or supports directly on the bed, with minimal bridging (hooray!)

Print this at 50% infill or above or else you'll have a heavy heart; a heart may lack structural integrity and deform when mounted under its own weight.

Make sure that you print at a fine enough resolution so that the chamfered underside of the fat connectors is properly formed. If this doesn't fit correctly, the parts will pop out.

Assembly

Let's say all the pieces are dumped on the floor and you don't know which is which.

  1. Start with part #1 (the V-shaped part lacking connectors) to assemble the top of the heart counter-clockwise
  2. Insert piece #2, which has a mounting hole and is curved.
  3. Insert piece #3, which has an embossed line.
  4. Insert piece #4, which does not have an embossed line.
  5. Continue until you've inserted all pieces.

If you have trouble finding the next piece, the odd pieces have an embossed line on them, whereas the even pieces do not. Pieces will always assemble in order, so the embossed lines should alternate.

Mounting

To prevent sagging, I've added four mount holes at strategic points. Four pushpins will hold the frame and an LED light cable to the wall.

description.text:
Base plate around LEGO with various wooden railways like Brio, Thomas and Friends etc. to use.

Printing the rail is very uncritical.

But the diameter of the LEGO knobs must be very accurate.
Each printer will print them slightly differently. In order not to have to try without need, I have created a test plate with knobs of 5 to 4.6 mm diameter. Each 3x6 per diameter.

After the test print you simply select the appropriate stl file.

The best slicer for LEGO knobs is simlify3d according to my tests.

The studs I extended for a better connection to 3mm (LEGO 1.85mm).

Be sure to provide good adhesion to the print bed.

I have intentionally used only the 144mm rail instead of the 216 standard rail to fit the component to most printers.

Please print only if you can make the nubs clean and accurate.

author: shadowjig

print_settings.Notes:: 'Horizontal expansion'

description.text:
Hi!

This one is a generator for some kind of 'Dragon/Alien Eggs' that can be used as a container for small pieces.

This is one of many experiments based in Phyllotaxis algorithms. Eventually i'll publish one or two more interesting things related to this.

This is a customizable figure. Play with the Customizer and find a nice one.

Every customization produces 4 files:

  • Complete sphere
  • Upper semisphere
  • Lower semisphere
  • Screw to join the semispheres

Print the two semispheres and the screw and you'll get the container.

Also the semispheres are great for a planter.

Use the complete sphere as you wish. You can throw a dragon inside while printing and get a real dragon egg. Wuhuu!

I encourage you to download and modify the OpenScad code. The Customizer made for this one just modify some parameters but dealing with code you can get many variations.

This one uses the Poor Mans Screw Library (sigthly modificated) for the screw and nuts used. ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8796 )

Also used this nice dragon of bs3: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1469139 in pictures.

Hope you enjoy this one!

Have fun!

Printer:

BQ Prusa i3 Hephestos

Rafts:

No

Notes:

Tested with PLA

Supports: You may need supports in some figures with big spikes. also the 'top' of inner sphere can make 'overhanging' issues and you may want some supports here. I usually cut and clean the overhangs.

Infill not needed but recomended as 'inner supports' for the figure. a 15-25% infill must be enough. I print some 'hollow' figures and may appear small holes on roofs

3 top layers it's great to avoid small holes on roofs

2 shells ant 2 bottom layers will be enough

Tested with resolutions between 0.3mms and 0.15mms (for big and smaller figures)

IMPORTANT!! Scale down by 1%-2% the XY axis (not Z) of screw and you'll get an easy and smooth screw without need of sanding

In Cura slicer sofware there's an option called 'Horizontal expansion'. Set this to -0.2 or -0.3 and print screw at same scale than semispheres.

Parameters

Part Shows one of the 4 files generated. Use Sphere to see the complete ball. The semispheres give an error as they took to many time to render due to screws inside.

ANGLE (also called phi) determines the spiral distribution of spikes and bulbs. Phyllotaxis it's about patterns found in nature. See the image bellow for some nice angles

Pattern 1 and Pattern 2 The algorithm alternates 2 kinds of geometry parts(spikes and bulbs) so you can select wich one will be the #1 or #2

Pattern 2 every... determines when draw the secon pattern. Changing this you'll get big difference between figures generated

Spikes scale scales the length of spikes by this factor

Spikes distribution make a sightly difference as the biggers are near top or near equator

Spikes variation:The spikes size may change along the sphere growing and shrinking. More variation -> more grow-shrinks of the spikes.

Bulb type determines the decoration of bulbs

The 4 files generated: 2 semispheres, a complete sphere and the screw Some scheme of phyllotaxis patterns and a bunch of nice angles to test. Customizer Samples

description.text:
This is an X-Axis carriage for my attempt at the Gada Intermediate Prize (for RepRap). The carriage mounts to four  bearing plates (which each hold three bearings), and thus moves along the X-Axis. This is a work in project; as you can tell, only the carriage exists, not the bearing plates, nor the other axis/related drive systems. This is purely experimental, also, as I don't have a 3D printer to print it on (yet; getting Mendel together has been tough!), so this is not known to print successfully.
The two holes are M4 diameter. They are used for mounting an extruder/head. The two columns/hole in the middle are quite obviously where the extruder supported/mounted through.

Once the bearing plates are up, assembly should be relatively straight forward. Instructions for mounting the bearings themselves will be on that page.
  • Step 1- Print all necessary parts.
  • Step 2- Prep-fit parts to ensure they snugly go together; if they don't, sand/file gently until a snug fit is reached)
  • Step 3- Apply desired gluing agent to pins on the bearing plate. This agent can be acetone, super-glue, epoxy, etc...
  • Step 4- LIGHTLY coat the four teardrop holes in the carriage with desired gluing agent
  • Step 5- Press together, until parts are flush.
  • Step 6- Let set until glue is dry.
    Done! You now have an X-Carriage!

It resembles todayâ€™s sets in most respects, but two of the pieces are different, so the set is actually a precursor of the modern version of the game, whose rules mostly arose in the late 15th century. In the museumâ€™s set, instead of queens, there are viziers, and instead of bishops, there are elephants, which were called fils, according to â€œMasterpieces From the Department of Islamic Art in the Metropolitan Museum of Art,â€ a book about the exhibition that is being published by the museum. The viziers and the elephants moved differently, and were less powerful, than their modern counterparts, which probably made the game slower and less exciting. The viziers could only move or capture diagonally one square at a time; the modern queen is allowed unlimited movement in any direction. The elephants moved diagonally two squares at a time, while modern bishops can move any number of diagonal squares. The viziers could never attack each other. Chess had started to spread to Europe a couple of centuries before the Metropolitanâ€™s Persian set was made and had already moved closer to the modern game there. These 3 designs are based on the steering wheel center cap from the Caresto Arkham Car that Caresto Cars (http://www.caresto.se/cargalle...) built for the Gumball 3000 race 2016.

These versions are flat and the scale is 50% compared to the originally 3D printed part. The original was 3D printed by Palmiga Innovation (http://rubber3dprinting.com/), using PI-ETPU 95-250 Carbon Black filament.

3 versions are available, one without holes, one that can be used as a key-chain token and one that for instance could be used to make a hanging mobile. You can probably find other uses too :- )

CARESTO ARKHAM CAR

This one of a kind car is built by Caresto to be part of Gumball 3000, 2016. The design is based on the car from the Arkham knight game but has been redesigned and manufactured with drivability and full functionality in mind. The car is BIG. The wheel base is 3.40 meters and the width of this special car is 2,5 meters. The special high rigid tubular frame is manufactured to provide good handling and give a solid feeling. Front and rear suspensions are fully independent and made with double wishbones connected to the coil over shock absorbers, up front through a special designed aluminum push rod. To power the car, we have used a 560hp V 10 engine connected to a paddle shift gear box affecting the 26" wheels. To stop the car we have used ABS supported 8-pot Brembo calipers in front and 6-pot in rear all connected to big brake discs. The complicated all carbon fiber body has been made from full scale moulds which are milled out from the CAD drawings. A lot of effort has been made to the design of the drawings and moulds. This to get the correct stance with full working systems and parts that will work together. Inside the car the driver and the passenger can enjoy the interior in a combination of black soft leather and "see trough" fabric, all kept together by golden stitches. The interior lights up in seats, floor and pedals when the cockpit opens up fully electrical operated. All comfort functions such as climate system, power steering, fantastic sound system, etc helps to make this car a comfortable driver, even that the look is hard as steel.

description.text:
German bellow

Vacuum cleaner cable Clip 45 mm to 8 mm

This almost unobtrusive fixture is the month of cable-guided machines connected to vacuum cleaners, such as grinding machines, milling, special drills and so on. This is the case, for example, when interior dwellings are being built.

The bracket fits 45 mm diameter vacuum cleaner tubing and can accommodate 6 to 8 mm power cables. Depending on the hose length, you need about 4-5 pieces of this clip and thanks to a guide rail inside, the clip can not slip on the hose back and forth. It is therefore ideal for construction workers, technicians and installers.

Staubsauger Kabelclip von 45 mm auf 8 mm

Diese fast schon unauffällige Halterung ist zur Monate von Kabelgeführten Maschinen, die an Staubsaugern angeschlossen werden, etwa Schleifmaschinen, Frässen, Spezial Bohrer und so weiter. Dies kommt zum Beispiel beim Innenausbau von Wohnungen vor.

Die Halterung passt an Staubsaugerschläuche mit 45 mm Durchmesser und kann Stromkabel von 6 - 8 mm aufnehmen. Je nach Schlauchlänge, benötigt man etwa 4-5 Stück dieses Clips und dank einer Führungsschiene im Inneren, kann der Clip nicht auf dem Schlauch hin und her Rutschen. Er ist also Ideal für Bauarbeiter, Techniker und Monteure.

description.text:
This is a remix of DavidJohnston's Parametric OpenSCAD Base for Intel 5th Generation NUC.

I've made a bunch of changes to tweak this project to my needs, including:
-Added mounting points for a 2.5" hard drive
-Added holes to mount rubber feet (reusable from the OEM NUC bottom)
-Anchored the screw columns to the box walls
-Improved ventilation
-Added brace for bottom ventilation slits
-Added optional "mouse ears" at each corner to keep print from lifting off the bed (these need to be cut away after printing is complete)

Please note that I'm not providing an STL file for this thing, only an SCAD file. There are many configurable options for this thing, so you'll need to open it in OpenSCAD, choose your options, render the thing, and then export it to an STL flie yourself.
